---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';
import CaseStudyFigure from '../components/CaseStudyFigure.astro';

const img = (file: string) => `images/case-studies/ixd/${file}`;

const nav = [
  { label: 'Overview', href: '#overview' },
  { label: 'Foundations', href: '#brand' },
  { label: 'Applications', href: '#applications' },
  { label: 'AI in Process', href: '#aiprocess' },
  { label: 'Reflection', href: '#reflection' },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="IXDA"
  heading="Building community through design"
  role="Creative Director, Designer"
  team="Solo Concept Project"
  timeline="1 week"
  projectType="Brand, Community"
  nav={nav}
>
  <section id="overview" data-comment-id="ixd-overview">
    <h3>context</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      My program did not have a year end show this year. So how might I use design to build a fresh
      and experience-lead event concept?
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      src={img('event-experience-collage.gif')}
      alt="Collage of IXDA year-end event concept materials including hoodies, pins, and name tags"
      caption="Event experience collage"
      wide
    />
  </section>

  <section id="brand" data-comment-id="ixd-brand">
    <h3>inspiration</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I won the hoodie design challenge run annually by the IXDA club (Sheridan Interaction Design
      Association). Since this design is validated as popular choice by the students in my program,
      I thought to turn this one-off design into a brand system.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      src={img('hoodie-concept-collage.png')}
      alt="IXDA hoodie concept with award ribbon and portfolio keychain mockup"
      caption="Hoodie design challenge — starting point for the brand system"
      wide
    />
    <h3>Concept</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Most people don't know what interaction design is. My hoodie design played on this, and drove
      the direction of my brand system. Create a space for audiences new to interaction design, a
      way to interact and experience it.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      My concept was to print the definition onto the sleeve. Budget constraints didn't allow, but
      the lesson stuck. Beyond strong visuals, audiences connect to interactive experiences.
    </p>
    <h3>brand tone</h3>
    <p class="lead">Minimal, bold, honest.</p>
    <h3>brand foundations</h3>
    <p>
      Typography is simple, letting the graphic elements and layout shine. Inter is also Figma's
      default font, calling back to the most used software in our program.
    </p>
    <p>
      Colour choice is simple and accessible in different combinations. Sheridan's brand colour is
      blue, but in a more vibrant tone.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      src={img('brand-foundations-system.png')}
      alt="IXDA System 01 brand foundations — atoms, typography scale, and Winter Frost colour way"
      caption="Brand foundations — typography, components, and colour"
      wide
    />
    <p>
      The Interaction Design Association runs the program's year end party and annual hoodie design
      challenge.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Sheridan IXDA club logo"
      caption="IXDA logo — image missing (*this logo was not designed by me)"
    />
    <p class="text-muted text-sm italic">*this logo was not designed by me</p>
    <p>
      This illustration represents our school mascot: the bruin, while also communicating a sense
      of reliability in its tired stance.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Bruin mascot illustration representing reliability"
      caption="Bruin mascot illustration — image missing"
    />
  </section>

  <section id="applications" data-comment-id="ixd-applications">
    <h3>applications</h3>
    <p>
      Every year, the IXDA club runs an award ceremony for new grads to vote on their peers during
      the year end party. My idea is that students can make their own award pins with their given
      superlative (or another tagline) as an activity to do with friends.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Custom award pin activity for year end party"
      caption="Award pin making activity — image missing"
    />
    <p>Sticker sheet border is used as a photo frame for a photobooth!</p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Photobooth frame using sticker sheet border"
      caption="Photobooth sticker frame — image missing"
    />
    <p>Website directory for this years new grad designers!</p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="New grad designer website directory"
      caption="Grad designer directory — image missing"
    />
    <p>
      Each attendee of the year end show gets a connect the dots card with a handwritten note and a
      way to keep track of which tables they have yet to visit! Each card has "interaction design"
      written in a different language. (you can't understand it in any language anyways…)
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Connect the dots card with interaction design in different languages"
      caption="Connect the dots attendee card — image missing"
    />
    <p>
      Every year, the IXDA club at Sheridan makes different limited edition pins that students can
      collect. This tote bag design helps students find a home for them! They can also put their
      award pin on it too!
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Tote bag design for collecting limited edition pins"
      caption="Pin collection tote bag — image missing"
    />
    <p>
      Using the Sheridan IXDA logo reference, each new grad's name tag will have a cohesive event
      identity.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="New grad name tag using IXDA logo reference"
      caption="Grad name tag — image missing"
    />
    <p>
      Instead of traditional large, crossbody portfolios, students can purchase our portfolio
      keychains to showcase their work in mini booklets and share their social links via NFC tags!
      (QR codes can be printed on the books as well if NFC is that compatible)
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="Portfolio keychain with mini booklet and NFC social links"
      caption="Portfolio keychain concept — image missing"
    />
  </section>

  <section id="aiprocess" data-comment-id="ixd-aiprocess">
    <h3>using ai in the process</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I used AI to generate mockups of my concepts. I used Figma Weave and AI tools within Figma and
      found that the tools/workflow doesn't matter as much as the context that you feed it.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      When I rely on flat lay designs that I designed only, it creates a design that is almost too
      perfect.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="AI mockup generated from flat lay design only"
      caption="AI mockup from flat lay only (too perfect) — image missing"
    />
    <p class="lead">
      When I use an award ribbon I made myself and took pictures of, it created a much more realistic
      mockup.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      placeholder
      alt="AI mockup generated using photographed award ribbon"
      caption="AI mockup with real-world photo context — image missing"
    />
  </section>

  <section id="reflection" data-comment-id="ixd-reflection">
    <h3>Reflections</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Don't wait for permission</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Design and build what you want to see, even if it's not yet possible.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Explore different tools</h2>
        <p class="lead">Find ways to achieve the vision with new tools.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <h3 class="!mt-12">next steps</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Pitch to Faculty</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Now that the concept is built out, I want to bring this to reality by getting buy in from
          faculty and external sponsors.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Build on with peers</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Building out large scale events is not a task for one. Gathering a community of like minded
          students is important to breath life into this concept.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>
</CaseStudyLayout>
